<HEADLINE>
<P>
LEGAL ON THE OUTSIDE, SCAM ON THE INSIDE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JOHN CRUDELE 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Because of the F. D. Roberts Securities case, investigators are getting a 
unique opportunity to see how a typical penny stock scam is put together. And 
what they are finding is enlightening: The people who operated F. D. Roberts 
were on the up-and-up in their handling of prospectuses and other documents 
that went to the Securities and Exchange Commission. But they were anything but 
truthful with the public. 
</P>
<P>
"They went through all the motions," said one investigator familiar with the 
case. The only trouble was that "very few people who invested ever got a 
prospectus," he adds. 
</P>
<P>
The only things that investors got were slick sales pitches, some high-pressure 
sales tactics, maybe a deceptive brochure and a lot of lies. Even the most 
naive investor probably wouldn't have sent F. D. Roberts a dime if he or she 
had seen what the brokerage firm was telling the SEC. 
</P>
<P>
Take Innovative Business Corp. as an example. 
</P>
<P>
Through F. D. Roberts, the company sold to the public 2,000 units -- with each 
unit consisting of 10,000 shares of company stock plus 10,000 common stock 
purchase warrants. Each unit was priced at $500 -- making the total offering 
worth $1 million. 
</P>
<P>
F. D. Roberts took a generous 10% fee from the money raised. And of the 
$900,000 earmarked for the company -- which was supposed to be in the market 
for corporate acquisitions -- another $100,000 would be gobbled up by expenses. 
</P>
<P>
That left Innovative Business with $800,000, which the prospectus clearly 
stated "may not be sufficient to complete one acquisition." 
</P>
<P>
Prosecutors said they don't believe that Innovative Business ever made an 
acquisition. But the company's stock, they said, still rose shortly after the 
initial public offering. And F. D. Roberts made a fortune. 
</P>
<P>
Integrated Business Corp. was an even crazier scheme. 
</P>
<P>
Its prospectus said the company had obtained an option to acquire a franchise 
from the U.S. Basketball League Inc. to operate a team in Tampa, Fla. Through 
F. D. Roberts, the company sold 12.5 million units at 2 cents each. Of the 
$250,000 raised, the prospectus said, only $210,000 would probably go to the 
company. And $30,000, or 13.5% of the total proceeds, would go to pay company 
executives. 
</P>
<P>
But that wasn't the worst part. The prospectus also stated that there were 
already 32.5 million shares outstanding -- presumably held by company insiders 
who cooked up the scheme. 
</P>
<P>
That meant that as soon as the initial offering was completed, the value of the 
units being sold to the public would automatically decline from the original 2 
cents to half a cent. 
</P>
<P>
Even so, through market manipulation on the part of F. D. Roberts, the 
company's virtually worthless shares were being quoted at prices far exceeding 
the level of the initial public offering, prosecutors said. 
</P>
<P>
But F. D. Roberts wasn't content just to make a sizable fee from taking these 
companies public. The companies typically would have friends and relatives of 
F. D. Roberts officials in top positions, drawing nice salaries. 
</P>
<P>
Prosecutors have also charged that F. D. Roberts and its brokers reaped huge 
commissions by trading excessively in clients' accounts. And, in manipulating 
the price of these stocks higher, F. D. Roberts was guaranteeing itself a 
bundle since Roberts officials have also been charged with illegally purchasing 
shares for themselves. 
</P>
<P>
F. D. Roberts, moreover, made it very difficult for the public to sell its 
stock. F. D. Roberts officials, their friends and relatives, on the other hand, 
had no trouble selling their stock holdings, officials said. This essentially 
created a pyramid scheme in which only a chosen few could capitalize on the 
manipulation of a stock's price. 
</P>
<P>
Additionally, F. D. Roberts was in the habit of granting to itself, at 
virtually no cost, warrants to purchase shares in most of the companies that it 
took public. This gave F. D. Roberts yet another way to cash in on its 
manipulation. JOHN CRUDELE 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Sidebar 
</P>
</TYPE>
<SUBJECT>
<P>
F D ROBERTS SECURITIES INC; SECURITIES FRAUD; INVESTMENT FRAUD; ORGANIZED 
CRIME; STOCK MARKET; INNOVATIVE BUSINESS CORP; INTEGRATED BUSINESS CORP; OVER 
THE COUNTER STOCKS 
</P>
</SUBJECT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA020490-0072 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 171304 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
February 4, 1990, Sunday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Business; Part D; Page 6; Column 1; Financial Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
1687 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
MOB'S MUSCLE CITED AS FORCE BEHIND F. D. ROBERTS PENNY STOCK SWINDLE; 
</P>
<P>
SECURITIES: A NEW JERSEY CASE BRINGS TO LIGHT HOW THE MAFIA MANAGED THE 
FRAUDULENT SECURITIES OPERATION AND ITS INTIMIDATING SALES TACTICS. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JOHN CRUDELE, SPECIAL TO THE TIMESJOHN CRUDELE is a financial columnist for 
the New York Post. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
When Scotty Lyons answered a tiny help-wanted advertisement for a stockbroker 
that he saw in his local Florida newspaper, he wouldn't have guessed that he'd 
end up working for the Mob. 
</P>
<P>
But it wasn't too long after getting that high-paying job at F. D. Roberts 
Securities Inc. in Boca Raton, Fla., that Lyons -- whose name has been changed 
here -- realized that the stocks he was peddling to gullible investors 
nationwide were worthless and that, more ominously, he had unknowingly become a 
participant in one of organized crime's hottest new schemes -- securities 
fraud. 
</P>
<P>
Even the most naive employee apparently knew of F. D. Roberts' underworld 
affiliation -- a connection that certain officials of the now-closed brokerage 
have admitted in court. 
</P>
<P>
Some of the low-level employees didn't care that they were working for the Mob, 
Lyons says. Others were such novices in the securities business that perhaps 
they didn't realize that what they were doing was very illegal. 
</P>
<P>
But all of the workers knew one thing. "Everybody knew not to screw with them," 
says Lyons now, months after having quit the "brokerage" business. "The 
intimidation factor was tremendous." 
</P>
<P>
Lyons agreed to discuss how he was recruited into a seemingly legitimate 
brokerage that federal prosecutors allege was nothing more than a business 
subsidiary of the New York-based Gambino organized crime family, which is 
reputedly headed by John Gotti. In return, some of the details about Lyons' 
past have been disguised, so that he doesn't have to have a reunion with his 
old employers. 
</P>
<P>
To start with, nobody really knows how deeply organized crime has infiltrated 
the business of selling penny stocks to the public, but several of the major 
crime families are believed to dabble in the business. There have been hearings 
before Congress about the matter, and investigators say the link between the 
Mob and the selling of worthless securities has been growing in recent years. 
</P>
<P>
Why? "It's such a fertile field," says Joseph G. Braunreuther, assistant U.S. 
attorney in Newark, N.J., where penny stock fraud prosecutions have become a 
specialty. "There is a lot of money to be made in the financial markets," he 
adds. 
</P>
<P>
Members of organized crime, of course, are not the only ones selling worthless 
stocks in bogus companies. There are thousands of enterprising thieves around 
the nation who -- with the aid of a printing press, a telephone and a deft 
sales pitch -- are selling securities that give new meaning to the phrase "junk 
market." 
</P>
<P>
Not all penny stocks are worthless. Some legitimate companies do start out 
small, with their stocks worth a fraction of what an established company's 
shares would be worth. 
</P>
<P>
But the case of F. D. Roberts -- which is being prosecuted successfully in New 
Jersey, the company's state of incorporation -- provides a unique peek into the 
role of the Mob in penny stock frauds. (The company formerly had branches in 
Los Angeles and Desert Hot Springs.) 
</P>
<P>
Prosecutors say organized crime brings a special talent to the stock fraud 
business -- intimidation. The muscle isn't used against the investors. Believe 
it or not, people voluntarily surrender millions of dollars a year to the 
smooth-talking operators of penny stock frauds, as Lyons explains. 
</P>
<P>
Instead, the Mob's muscle comes in handy if any of the co-conspirators in a 
stock fraud decide that they no longer feel comfortable stealing from 
investors. "Not much (muscle) is needed," says Braunreuther, explaining that an 
implied threat is usually enough to make any white-collar criminal buckle. 
</P>
<P>
Most penny stock frauds are similar to the age-old pyramid schemes. Here's how 
the Mob, for instance, would put one of these scams together: 
</P>
<P>
First, the mobsters would launder illegally obtained money by bankrolling the 
start of a new company that, let's say, will purportedly own shopping centers. 
The company wouldn't be given a whole lot of capital -- just enough so that it 
can buy a property or two and be able to promise convincingly in legal 
documents that it plans to buy more buildings. 
</P>
<P>
Then, a large amount of stock that far exceeds the company's actual worth is 
sold by a small number of closely related "brokerages" that specialize in penny 
stocks. The sales are made over the telephone, with names of potential clients 
coming from mailing lists and referrals. 
</P>
<P>
The company never really plans to purchase more buildings. That's just a ruse. 
</P>
<P>
What the company -- which is usually run by close associates or relatives of 
the mobsters -- and its brokers really intend to do is manipulate the price of 
the shares upward so that investors will continually be enticed into buying 
stock. 
</P>
<P>
This way, not only do the schemers sell their personal stock holdings in the 
company at inflated prices as the stock rises, but the brokers and their firms 
also make fortunes from excessive trading commissions generated from the stock 
purchases. 
</P>
<P>
The key to all this is that nobody can be allowed to break with the conspiracy. 
If one of the brokerages stops trading the manipulated stock at the falsely 
inflated price, then the whole deceit unravels. That's where the Mob comes in: 
It keeps everyone in line. 
</P>
<P>
But, as Lyons explained, it wasn't all that difficult for the folks running F. 
D. Roberts to keep its troops loyal. There were, after all, plenty of economic 
incentives. 
</P>
<P>
Lyons said he personally made more than $100,000 in sales commissions in his 
first two months on the job, and it wasn't unusual for office managers to pull 
in $100,000 a month. 
</P>
<P>
That's big money for anyone, but it is especially enticing when you consider 
that F. D. Roberts had a habit of recruiting lesser-paid workers -- like 
bartenders barely out of their teens -- into its version of the brokerage 
business. "One guy was sleeping in a laundry room" before he was hired by F. D. 
Roberts, Lyons said. 
</P>
<P>
As if that weren't enough to ensure loyalty, there also was the French chef 
hired by Roberts to provide sustenance for its troops during business hours; 
the evening beer blasts that went on even as brokers were making calls to 
clients on the West Coast, and "phenomenal" parties at the Boca Raton Resort 
&amp; Club. 
</P>
<P>
But F. D. Roberts also expected a lot of its brokers. 
</P>
<P>
Lyons said the 60 or so brokers at the Boca Raton office were required to be at 
work before 9 a.m. each day or be fined $100. At 9:30 a.m. they'd be given a 
pep talk that would have made a Big 10 college football coach proud. 
</P>
<P>
At that meeting, the managers would tell the brokers which stocks would be 
manipulated higher in price that day. They'd be encouraged to sell, sell, sell. 
A manager might fling a piece of gold jewelry to the previous day's most 
successful salesman. 
</P>
<P>
One manager even ushered his brokers to the office window so they could be 
inspired by the sight of the manager's new Rolls-Royce Corniche being delivered 
on cue in the parking lot. That car sells for more than $140,000, and the 
brokers were well aware that the manager also had a Mercedes and a Porsche at 
home. 
</P>
<P>
Lyons said the message was: "You do your work, and see what you can get." 
</P>
<P>
The brokers would spend their entire day calling clients from coast to coast. 
Some used scripts prepared for them by F. D. Roberts; other brokers would wing 
it. All were specially trained in high-pressure sales techniques. 
</P>
<P>
If a prospective client said, "I can't make that sort of investment without 
consulting my spouse," the broker would typically deride him or her by saying, 
"Who's the boss in your family anyway?" 
</P>
<P>
If the client's objection was that the money was being set aside for a child's 
education, the broker might say, "Do you really think you'll be able to afford 
a good college education investing the way you are now?" 
</P>
<P>
And if an investor insisted that he needed more time to think it over, the 
broker would offer to fill out the forms to buy stock now, "and you can always 
cancel the order later." Later, if the client did try to cancel, he would be 
told that it was too late. 
</P>
<P>
His protests would be cut short when the broker told him that the price of the 
stock he bought had already risen. (The stock, of course, actually did go up 
because the brokerage was manipulating it higher.) 
</P>
<P>
The brokers weren't above a little play acting, either. On more than one 
occasion, a broker's confederates would create background noises of ticker tape 
machines by tapping on their staplers. "Oh, oh," the broker would tell his mark 
over the phone, "another 100 shares of XYZ stock just traded. You'd better 
hurry or you'll miss out." 
</P>
<P>
Brokers in the Boca Raton office were expected to stay on the phone for hours. 
"If you weren't on the phone, they'd pull your chair away and make you stand up 
to get motivated," Lyons says. 
</P>
<P>
The sales staff was really pumped up, Lyons said, whenever the brokerage was 
starting a new scam. "They'd have an emergency meeting at 2 p.m. and say, 'This 
stock is coming out; have everyone buy it.' They guaranteed that the price 
would go up," Lyons says. 
</P>
<P>
But only certain clients -- mostly close associates of the brokerage's owners 
-- would ever be permitted to sell their stocks once the price did go up. 
Often, a broker was told that he had to deliver two new clients to buy a stock 
at a higher price for every one client who wanted out. 
</P>
<P>
Sometimes, Roberts just wouldn't let a client sell. One client, according to 
Lyons, was told that sell orders for a particular stock were being taken in the 
alphabetical order of the clients' last names. Since this particular client's 
name began with "W," he'd just have to wait his turn. 
</P>
<P>
If a client persisted, the broker would simply "fire" the client, said Lyons. 
The broker would mail the client the worthless stock certificate. Of course, 
the client would never be able to sell the stock anywhere else. 
</P>
<P>
So far, New Jersey prosecutors have gotten 17 guilty pleas in the F. D. Roberts 
case. And New Jersey securities regulators have filed a civil complaint against 
more than a dozen officials of the firm, alleging that it made $65 million in 
illegal trading profits. Additional criminal charges are likely to be filed as 
well, according to law enforcement sources. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Reputed mob boss John Gotti, currently on trial in New York. Associated 
Press 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
