<HEADLINE>
<P>
ARCHBISHOP ROGER MAHONY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The highly charged emotional issues of abortion and cigarette smoking in public 
places have this in common: They restrict population growth, one by 
forestalling the birth of unwanted children and the other by escalating the 
death rate; and they polarize perfectly nice, reasonable people instantly into 
bitter enemies, ready to do bodily harm at the least provocation! Take good 
Archbishop Mahony, for instance. A pleasant regular guy -- jogs, flies his own 
helicopter, says "geez," talks just like you, me and the other fellas down at 
the health club. 
</P>
<P>
But when the subject of abortion comes up, watch out! This mild-mannered Dr. 
Jekyll metamorphoses -- in a trice -- into fire-breathing Mr. Hyde! Never mind 
that overpopulation causes most of the world's problems, and that most Latino 
families live in squalor. "There is no such thing as a pro-choice Catholic 
public official." To perpetuate such archaic, arbitrary, dilatory dogma, the 
archbishop (and the Vatican) must be running scared. And with good reason! 
</P>
<P>
MARVIN H. LEAF, Rancho Mirage 
</P>
</TEXT>
