Photo Archives; Photo, Muscle Beach acrobatics (right) were popular in 1948 
when Guy Dyer McGonagill was a teen-ager. However, when he became a lifeguard a 
year later, McGonagill (below, second from left) and his friends preferred 
luaus. ; Photo, In 1954, Miller's mother (not pictured) and two aunts, Lee 
Ellsworth (standing, second from right) and Florence Ellsworth (standing, fifth 
from left), belonged to a black women's social club. ; Photo, COLOR, In 1958, 
girls such as Marian Saxon (above, center) wore circle skirts and hairdos with 
bangs; on Friday nights, teen-agers cruised Whittier Boulevard, including 
Nixon's drive-in restaurant. ; Photo, Decades ago, nightclubs such as Ciro's 
(top) lined Sunset Boulevard. But the number of posh L.A. restaurants could be 
counted on one hand. One of them was Romanoff's on Rodeo Drive, as advertised 
on a matchbook (center). ; Photo, Kids considered eating at Clifton's 
Cafeterias a treat; some even saved a booklet (right) about the restaurants' 
unusual design. At a 1954 L.A. City College dance (bottom right), Sheffield 
takes the floor. ; Photo, COLOR, For Simon, growing up in Westwood was filled 
with carefree days of bus rides to MacArthur Park and sunbathing in her 
friends' back yards. ; Photo, While she was a high school student, Simon 
(second from right) and her classmates attended a private party at the Cocoanut 
Grove in 1953. ; Photo, In the '50s, downtown L.A. ballrooms were popular among 
