<HEADLINE>
<P>
OUTTAKES: FELIX AND OSCAR II? 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Daniel Cerone 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Jack Lemmon, Walter Matthau, writer Neil Simon and producer Howard W. Koch -- 
last seen together in 1968 working on the hit film "The Odd Couple" -- recently 
powwowed at the Beverly Hills Tennis Club. Subject of conversation: an "Odd 
Couple" sequel. 
</P>
<P>
"This is not a sequel like 'Police Academy 5,' " Koch told us. "We would pick 
up their lives 20 years later. They're older people now, not old men, but 
older. They have families and children. The comedic values are there, plus the 
dramatic values are there." 
</P>
<P>
Prior to the meeting, Matthau said of a possible sequel: "I'm sure (Koch) would 
prefer to call it 'The Odd Couple 2' to cash in on the words 'Odd Couple.' I 
was never for sequels, myself. Always avoided them. But I'm open to anything. I 
certainly wouldn't close my mind to fellows like Neil Simon, Jack Lemmon and 
Howard Koch." 
</P>
<P>
Simon's "The Odd Couple" has resurfaced in several forms since premiering on 
Broadway with Matthau and Art Carney in 1965, including a hit TV series and a 
female stage version. 
</P>
<P>
"We've always talked about doing a sequel through the years," Koch said. "It's 
been bothering me that we hadn't done it." So Koch asked for the meeting. "We 
came up with an idea for a story that we all agreed on. Neil said he would do 
it as soon as he can get some free time to write it, and then we'll go from 
there." Daniel Cerone 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
