</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
OUTTAKES: BATTER UP -- AGAIN 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Pat H. Broeske 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Following a barrage of pictures about men on the baseball diamond, Hollywood's 
going to make one about women who play the game. 
</P>
<P>
Penny Marshall will exec produce "A League of Their Own," based on the 
real-life All American Girls Professional Baseball League, which played from 
1942-53. 
</P>
<P>
For 20th Century Fox, "League" will roll in the Midwest in June, with David 
Anspaugh ("Hoosiers") directing. Lowell Ganz and Babaloo Mandell ("Parenthood") 
scripted. 
</P>
<P>
Set in the '40s, the story involves the league's origin -- during the 
man-shortage of World War II -- and focuses on the lives of two team members: a 
young mother whose husband is off fighting, and her teen-age sister. Pat H. 
Broeske 
</P>
</TEXT>
