<HEADLINE>
<P>
ROCKETS STILL HAVEN'T LEFT THE LAUNCH PAD 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By STEVE CAMPBELL, FT. WORTH STAR-TELEGRAM 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
HOUSTON 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
To Don Chaney's horror, the Houston Rockets have gone from envisioning a 
championship to plugging holes in a sinking ship. 
</P>
<P>
Mayday: The Rockets are two percentage points ahead of Seattle and one-half 
game behind Golden State in the race for the final spot in the Western 
Conference playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
Mayday: The same team Chaney predicted before the season would win 50 games is 
on a pace for 39. 
</P>
<P>
Mayday: Houston is 4-19 on the road after a 98-91 loss at Dallas Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
One of the few victories Chaney got in December, when the Rockets went 3-12, 
was a moral one. 
</P>
<P>
"We didn't get any finger-pointing," Chaney said. "And one reason, maybe, is a 
because we all played poorly. You couldn't point without pointing at yourself." 
</P>
<P>
Akeem Olajuwon, who averages 23.3points and leads the league with 13.4rebounds 
and 4.1blocked shots per game, has been one of the few bright spots. But he too 
has been frustrated. 
</P>
<P>
"We know this team cannot win a championship," Olajuwon told a Houston TV 
station last month. "There's no reason deceiving ourselves now because in the 
league you have to play seven-game (playoff) series. There's no luck. 
</P>
<P>
"You have to have the team to win, and it's going to take a lot more to win a 
championship. So we are not close." 
</P>
<P>
An 8-5 record in January has helped calm Olajuwon. But the Rockets played eight 
of those games at home. 
</P>
<P>
"Our championship focus is not on this year," Chaney said. "We're building for 
the future. You can't build and talk about a championship at the same time and 
be very realistic. 
</P>
<P>
"To focus on a championship, you've got to be in the playoffs. Our main focus 
is to get to .500. Then climb above .500. Then get a playoff spot. Then when 
you get in the playoffs, maybe." 
</P>
<P>
During the preseason, however, Chaney said that the Rockets "on paper" had the 
makings of a 50-victory team. The Rockets were coming off a 45-victory season. 
</P>
<P>
They had signed rebounding fiend Larry Smith and playmaker John Lucas as free 
agents. Off-guards Mitchell Wiggins and Lewis Lloyd both were back from 2 
1/2-year drug suspensions. Forwards Otis Thorpe, Buck Johnson and Derrick 
Chievous (average age: 25) would do nothing but improve. 
</P>
<P>
On paper. 
</P>
<P>
"I think we put pressure on ourselves to start out so well," Lucas said. "The 
expectations were so high. It kind of hurt us. We lost a lot of confidence when 
we lost the first game of the season." 
</P>
<P>
The Rockets opened the season Nov. 2 with a 102-88 road defeat to the Los 
Angeles Clippers. Because of a blood clot in his left calf, Olajuwon sat out 
all the exhibition games and was not at full speed at the beginning of the 
season. 
</P>
<P>
The Rockets were 9-6 entering December. But they lost at home to Dallas and New 
Jersey and on the road to Charlotte. During that stretch, Wiggins sprained his 
left knee and missed 16 games. Smith missed six games with a back injury. 
</P>
<P>
"When you're having those things happen, you have a tendency to feel sorry for 
yourselves," Chaney said. "You let a team like New Jersey beat you, Charlotte 
beat you, and you're at an all-time low. The Clippers had injuries and were 
short of talent, but they had plenty of confidence. They were taking open shots 
and just not making them. This team went out there with their heads down, and 
that scared me." 
</P>
<P>
The Rockets have been unable to provide consistent support for Olajuwon. In the 
last two months, the Rockets lost games in which Olajuwon had point and rebound 
totals of 41 and 14, 32 and 20, 33 and 17, and 34 and 12. 
</P>
<P>
With inconsistent outside shooting, defenses have sagged on Olajuwon and Otis 
Thorpe (16.5 points per game) in the Rockets' half-court offense. 
</P>
<P>
Chaney wants the Rockets to push the ball up the court, but they still rank 
only 19th in the NBA in scoring (103.6 ppg). 
</P>
<P>
"When we're running, we're in games," Chaney said. "When we're standing, we're 
in trouble." 
</P>
<P>
Wiggins, 30, has been a pleasant surprise. He averages 19.8points on 
50.7-percent shooting. Before his suspension, he averaged 9.6 points on 
46-percent shooting. 
</P>
<P>
"If I had come back and averaged four or five points a game, people would have 
said, 'Seeing how he he has been out 2 1/2 years, that's about right,' " 
Wiggins said. "Nobody has ever come back like that. It's a lot better than I 
expected." 
</P>
<P>
Wiggins may serve as a reminder that there's always hope. 
</P>
<P>
Besides, the Rockets still have Olajuwon, whom Lucas refers to as "our Joe 
Montana. Without 'The Dream,' we would already be sitting up in New York 
(awaiting the draft lottery) saying, 'Number, please.' " 
</P>
</TEXT>
