<P>
ARMAND ARABIAN 
</P>
<SECTION>
<P>
Part A; Page 3; Column 5; Metro Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
1415 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
NOMINEE ARABIAN CALLED IN THE MOLD OF GOVERNOR'S CHOICES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By PHILIP HAGER, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
SAN FRANCISCO 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Gov. George Deukmejian's newest nominee to the state Supreme Court is a 
pragmatic, moderately conservative but sometimes unpredictable judge who seems 
much in the mold of the governor's previous appointees, legal analysts said 
Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
State Appeal Court Justice Armand Arabian, 55, of Los Angeles could provide key 
votes in close cases -- as did the man he is succeeding, Justice Marcus M. 
Kaufman, some experts said. 
</P>
<P>
The governor formally named Arabian as his choice for the $115,161-a-year job 
on Saturday. Kaufman, who officially left the court on Wednesday, proved to be 
a judicial maverick who sometimes parted company with the four other Deukmejian 
appointees on the court and joined the court's liberal minority in some key 
cases. 
</P>
<P>
"Arabian has a real streak of chutzpah," said Santa Clara University law dean 
Gerald F. Uelmen, a close observer of the court. "I think he may display an 
independent streak that might make him a good replacement for Kaufman." 
</P>
<P>
Ellis J. Horvitz, an Encino attorney who appears often in civil cases before 
the court, described the new nominee as a judicial moderate and pragmatist -- 
and a potential court maverick, like Kaufman. "Nobody will ever doubt where 
Arabian stands," the lawyer said. "He's very up front." 
</P>
<P>
"The court now is not made up of ideologues or academicians, but justices who 
want to know how their decision will affect people -- they're concerned with 
practical effects," Horvitz said. "Arabian will fit right into that." 
</P>
<P>
Another court authority, UC Berkeley law professor Stephen R. Barnett, 
expressed doubt that Arabian would fill Kaufman's shoes as a frequent and 
sometimes outspoken dissenter. 
</P>
<P>
"He is a solid, workmanlike and conservative judge who respects constitutional 
rights, but he is unlikely to bring much balance or diversity to the views of 
the court," Barnett said. "But he seems to be more predictably conservative 
than Kaufman." 
</P>
<P>
A review of some of the highlights of Arabian's 18-year career on the bench 
reveals a mixture of judicial results. In criminal cases, for example, there is 
no evidence that he is heavily inclined toward either the prosecution or 
defense. Arabian served both as a prosecutor and defense lawyer earlier in his 
career, and as a judge he has proved tough on criminal defendants but also has 
reversed convictions when a significant procedural error has occurred. 
</P>
<P>
In civil cases, a recent study by Fred J. Hiestand, counsel to the Assn. for 
California Tort Reform, showed that Arabian often has ruled to protect 
defendants from damage awards, but the study also revealed instances where he 
has upheld the claims of plaintiffs. For example, in one instance, he ruled for 
a widow who sought more than $300,000 in damages from a group of investors for 
failing to provide her with proper advice. 
</P>
<P>
Whether issuing an opinion for the majority or raising a dissent, Arabian has 
sometimes exhibited a colorful writing style. 
</P>
<P>
In limiting an award to a waitress for sexual harassment by an employer, 
Arabian held that under the law, the state Fair Employment and Housing 
Commission was no more entitled to order compensatory and punitive damages than 
it "could order sterilization, castration or lobotomy." 
</P>
<P>
When the majority ruled that a convenience store could be sued by a customer 
who was assaulted by thugs after he had left the premises, Arabian vigorously 
objected. It was improper, he said in a dissent, to cite as evidence of the 
store's liability the fact that previously it had occasionally summoned police 
to protect customers. 
</P>
<P>
"A caring society is ennobled and enriched when citizen observers sound the 
alarm which seeks a protective response," he wrote. "The majority view has the 
practical effect of discouraging activities which benefit the victims amongst 
us. Do they seek to sanction the deafening silence which responded to the cry 
of Kitty Genovese?" 
</P>
<P>
In other notable Court of Appeal cases, Arabian has: 
</P>
<P>
* Refused to allow a candidate for public office to sue the Los Angeles County 
Bar Assn. for libel for saying he was unfit for the job; the Bar was entitled 
to its opinion, and the candidate had made himself a public figure open to such 
criticism, he said. 
</P>
<P>
* Affirmed the right of non-Christians to place advertisements in a publication 
called the Christian Yellow Pages. 
</P>
<P>
* Refused to exclude evidence from a surreptitiously recorded conversation 
between a 17-year-old murder suspect and his mother in which the boy admitted, 
"we did it, but I didn't pull the trigger." Arabian held there was no 
reasonable expectation of privacy in such conversations, adding, "indeed, in 
the jail house the age-old truism still pertains: 'walls have ears.' " 
</P>
<P>
* Ruled unconstitutional a state law that limited personal injury awards to 
uninsured motorists, finding that the statute violated the right to due 
process. 
</P>
<P>
* Upheld a state law aimed at preserving the matrimonial family and refused to 
grant an unmarried man visitation rights to a young girl he claimed was his 
daughter. The law presumes the co-habitating husband of the mother is the 
father, and although the unmarried man submitted a blood test indicating that 
he probably was the father, he was not entitled to visitation rights, the court 
said. 
</P>
<P>
Arabian has had wide experience on the bench -- a characteristic common of the 
seven appointees Deukmejian has made to the high court since he became governor 
in 1983. 
</P>
<P>
In announcing the appointment on his weekly radio address, the governor said: 
"During his tenure on the municipal, superior and appellate courts, he has 
earned a reputation for well-reasoned legal opinions, intellectual honesty, 
open-mindedness and a great ability to analyze tough legal problems." 
</P>
<P>
Deukmejian also took note of the nominee's sense of humor -- a quality cited by 
others who have known Arabian. One lawyer told how he has sometimes mis-dialed 
the Court of Appeal clerk's office and reached Arabian by mistake. The first 
time, Arabian quickly corrected him but in subsequent incidents the justice has 
playfully deceived the lawyer into a longer conversation, and, when the joke 
had played out, revealed his identity and told the attorney, "You've done it 
again!" 
</P>
<P>
Arabian, believed to be the first person of Armenian heritage named to the 
state high court, grew up in an Armenian community in New York and later, after 
moving to California, continued to display a vigorous interest in Armenian 
affairs. 
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the Los Angeles Daily Journal legal newspaper in 1983, 
Arabian remarked: "Being a member of an oppressed minority has sensitized me to 
certain positions in society. My family was a victim of Turkish oppression. My 
grandfather was shot by a firing squad. My family was put on a death march. 
They struggled to these golden shores in America." 
</P>
<P>
He also has been a longtime friend and supporter of Deukmejian -- and his name 
has been mentioned repeatedly in recent years when vacancies have arisen on the 
court. 
</P>
<P>
But authorities on Saturday discounted the suggestion that cronyism led to the 
nomination. "The appointment is fully justified on the merits of experience and 
ability," said attorney Horvitz. "If the governor wants to appoint an old 
friend who is also a first-rate jurist, more power to him." Added Uelmen: 
"There is no suggestion he is any less qualified than anyone else in the field 
from which he was selected. 
</P>
<P>
As a trial judge, Arabian won wide attention when in 1973 he refused to give 
jurors a then-required instruction to view a rape victim's testimony with 
caution. Two years later, the state Supreme Court struck down the instruction. 
</P>
<P>
Arabian wrote several legal articles on the subject that were used in attempts 
to overturn similar instructions in other states. He also worked closely with 
then-state Sen. Deukmejian and other legislators for mandatory prison sentences 
for rapists. 
</P>
<P>
In another case as a trial judge, Arabian once moved the entire court -- 
including the jury, lawyers and defendant -- to the small home of an 
83-year-old burglary victim who was unable to come to the courthouse to 
testify. 
</P>
<P>
Arabian's name also made the headlines in 1979 when then-Lt. Gov. Mike Curb 
sought to appoint him to the Court of Appeal while Gov. Edmund G. (Jerry) Brown 
Jr. was traveling out of state. When Brown returned, he rescinded the 
appointment. 
</P>
<P>
Later, the state Supreme Court held that while Curb did hold appointive power 
while Brown was out of state, Brown also had authority to pull back the 
nomination when he returned. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Profile 
</P>
</TYPE>
<SUBJECT>
<P>
POLITICAL APPOINTMENTS; DEUKMEJIAN, GEORGE; JUDGES -- CALIFORNIACALIFORNIA 
SUPREME COURT 
</P>
</SUBJECT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA020490-0237 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 279324 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
February 4, 1990, Sunday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<P>
CHUCK D (SINGER) 
</P>
<SECTION>
<P>
Calendar; Page 64; Calendar Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
2755 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
RAP-THE POWER AND THE CONTROVERSY; 
</P>
<P>
CHUCK D. -- THE INTERVIEW 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Chuck D. was interviewed by pop music critic Robert Hilburn in a New York 
recording studio as Public Enemy finished work on its third album, "Fear of a 
Black Planet." Rap's most acclaimed and controversial figure speaks candidly 
about the uproar surrounding his group, his music, his personal politics and 
the role of rap music in America. 
</P>
<P>
Hilburn: How fairly do you think you have been portrayed in the media -- the 
accusations of anti-Semitism in the band and so forth? 
</P>
<P>
Chuck D.: Everybody's not here to like you. . . . I think the key to being a 
wise black man in this hemisphere is in knowing that what you do is going to 
turn some people off because your perspective is different from others. You've 
got to (tell yourself), "No matter what I do, they're not going to see it from 
my eyes." 
</P>
<P>
Let's look at your perspective. What first got you interested in music? Who 
were your heroes as a kid? 
</P>
<P>
My heroes and role models came from sports. . . . Basketball . . . baseball . . 
. football. . . . People like Hank Aaron, Willie Mays, Willis Reed, Gale Sayers 
. . . a lot of black heroes. 
</P>
<P>
But my main man was Muhammad Ali. He was one of the first black men to come 
along and speak his mind. He'd go like, "Yo, not only did I whip this kid's ass 
(in the ring), but I'm smart. I look good. You can't push me around." Some 
people didn't like the fact that after he won, he thanked God and his religion. 
It was something they didn't understand. 
</P>
<P>
I think that a lot of people in America are really happy that Muhammad Ali is 
in the condition that he is in (Ali has been diagnosed as having Parkinson's 
syndrome) because back when he was in top-notch condition, yelling and stuff, 
(a lot of white people) didn't like him. They'd say, "I wish he would shut up." 
Reggie Jackson was another articulate brother who not only would beat you on 
the field, but he would (speak up in interviews) and say, "Yo, this is the way 
I did it." 
</P>
<P>
Did watching them inspire you -- and tell you about the dangers of being 
outspoken? 
</P>
<P>
Sure, it showed what happens when you rock the boat, but I think that if we sit 
still in the boat, we ain't going to get nowhere. The thing I saw in these 
sports heroes was that they were men. My father was my number one hero because 
he was a man, too. That's why all this that comes down today (around Public 
Enemy) doesn't bother me because I'm a man. Respect me as a man and I'll 
respect you. 
</P>
<P>
There's a lot of social commentary in your music. When did you start thinking 
about the world in those terms? 
</P>
<P>
My mom was active in lots of community-oriented things (on Long Island), and 
she put me into these special summer school (programs) when I was around 11 or 
12 and they taught us a lot about black history. In the beginning, it was fun 
because we were getting free sandwiches and apples and going to the pool, but 
we learned all kinds of other things that were helpful to me later . . . about 
the black community pulling together. . . . 
</P>
<P>
Rappers can do a lot of good because we have control of the media and that's 
why we're not liked because never before has the black man or so many black 
males spoken their opinion on so many things. 
</P>
<P>
Before (the message to blacks was), "You can do all kinds of crazy (expletive) 
on the basketball court, on the baseball field, then you can be a white boy's 
hero." 
</P>
<P>
Today, the problem is that people like Ice Cube or BDP are white boy's heroes, 
but they aren't just dealing from a physical thing, but a mental thing. 
</P>
<P>
Because of the problems your group went through last year, did you identify 
with the controversy involving N.W.A and the FBI's attack on their music? 
</P>
<P>
I understood what they were going through because it was the same thing most 
black people go through. If you have a (door) to the media and people don't 
understand what you are saying, people are going to come at you in all 
directions . . . and all (we both were doing) was addressing what is going on 
in our minds, what we see . . . asking questions. 
</P>
<P>
What were your goals in the first album? 
</P>
<P>
I tried to relate, "This is how we are thinking and how we are living on the 
block." If someone wants to know what the problem is with black America today, 
they'll go to some kind of social analyst who is making about $100,000 a year, 
living in a certain neighborhood and he's going to try to come from a point of, 
"This is what I see is wrong with the black situation." 
</P>
<P>
What were you saying in the lyrics on the first album? 
</P>
<P>
I was tackling issues, things I thought needed explaining. I remember back at 
that time, the media threw a lot of (expletive) at Run-DMC for the gang 
violence at the Long Beach concert. They blamed rap for violence and I thought 
that's crazy. How in the hell can they blame a music for violence when this is 
a situation that was festering in that area for years? It's a social situation. 
It ain't got nothing to do with rap. . . . 
</P>
<P>
That's when I decided to get involved in this and go head on head and toe to 
toe with the media because the media took a smack at rap music and Run-DMC 
because they didn't understand what was really going on in black life. 
</P>
<P>
So, I decided to play a little game on the media. I set traps for them. When I 
wrote, "My Uzi Weighs a Ton," I wanted to see people come out and say, "Damn, 
he's talking about Uzis" and start thinking about people walking around with 
real Uzis -- and they did it. Lots of people thought it was irresponsible, us 
talking about arming blacks and marching around with Uzis. 
</P>
<P>
Isn't there danger in that? Shouldn't you try to say things that people 
understand, rather than say things that confuse them? 
</P>
<P>
No, because I might say things that the media understands or the average white 
man understands, but then I might not be communicating with the black audience, 
which is my main audience. 
</P>
<P>
When people started asking about Uzis, did you feel you were able to explain 
your feelings? 
</P>
<P>
I know the message got out to my audience. There might have been a few brothers 
who thought, "Hell, yes" and liked the idea of carrying a gun, but I know that 
85 to 90% felt, "Yo, we know what he's saying." I know people keep saying, "Why 
don't you be perfectly clear?" Well, that's not rap because black society isn't 
perfectly clear to the white world. If you are speaking primarily to the black 
community, you are going to always run into problems with the white world. 
</P>
<P>
Why the military outfits on stage and the imitation Uzis? 
</P>
<P>
The idea came partly from the Black Panthers, which remains such a strong image 
in the black community. You've got to understand, the Black Panthers were 
looked upon as terrorists by the white community, but much of the black 
community looked upon them as heroes. 
</P>
<P>
The guns on stage symbolize why black people are in the situation they are in 
today. . . . the Europeans had the guns and took us out of Africa and sent us 
to America. The guns are us saying, "OK, never again is our culture going to be 
snatched away from us the way it was before." 
</P>
<P>
What about the second album? Which themes were most important to you in "It 
Takes a Nation of Millions to Hold Us Back"? 
</P>
<P>
That album was addressed right at the black community, the need to get our 
(expletive) together, to network, because no one is going to do it for us. The 
next album, which is "Fear of a Black Planet," is going to talk about what 
Caucasians believe about themselves. 
</P>
<P>
For me, I don't believe in black and white. There is no such thing. I believe 
that the original black man from Africa was the original seed and everything 
sprouted from there. If you want to look into genetics, the black man is able 
to reproduce everything on the color wheel . . . blond hair, blue eyes, light 
skin. 
</P>
<P>
The only reason people talk about separation is because the white world 
supremacists keep saying the white race is pure and that anything that mixes 
with it contaminates it. It's rooted in a lot of religions today and even in 
the law. If you decide to be with a black woman, your child is black. 
</P>
<P>
That second album was also information for the white audience to check out. The 
idea wasn't to exclude the white audience, but the title shows who it was 
addressed to. . . . The thinking: Our strength is in ourselves. The challenge 
is working against the people who want to hold us back. 
</P>
<P>
How did you feel when it was hailed by critics? 
</P>
<P>
For a lot of "white" people to say, "Damn, I've learned something about the 
black perspective," it was gratifying. I'm hu-man, I feel good when someone 
says, "Great job." 
</P>
<P>
But you must realize some people just respond to the music, not the themes. Is 
that enough for you? 
</P>
<P>
I think music should be regarded No. 1 as communication. That's what all us 
rappers are -- communicators. That's why a lot of people react so strongly 
against us. 
</P>
<P>
But pop music and soul music have a history of artists who have stressed 
socially conscious themes. What about Marvin Gaye, Stevie Wonder, Curtis 
Mayfield? 
</P>
<P>
But all that was just singing. It's not as direct. With rap, there is no way to 
miss the point of the song. 
</P>
<P>
What about the Griff situation and the Washington Times interview? 
</P>
<P>
I felt something was going to come down. I think Griff was disillusioned about 
a lot of things going on with his position (in the group). In the interview, he 
was trying to deal with this guy, talking about capitalistic exploitation of 
black people in South Africa and the involvement of different governments and 
he didn't have his facts down to a T. He was wrong. 
</P>
<P>
But why not remove Griff and just do away with the whole racism and 
anti-Semitic image, which is going to detract from the positive message that 
you feel is in your music? 
</P>
<P>
Because, you don't remove it as an issue by getting rid of Griff. You might 
remove it as an issue with you or with the Jewish constituency or the white 
public, but I told you I am mainly talking to my community, the black 
community, and they look at us a some kind of a hero. 
</P>
<P>
So when you fire Griff, they go, "Yo, you gave in to the white boy. . . . 
You're no different than everybody else. What kind of a leader are you?" The 
important thing to me was to make it clear that I thought what Griff said was 
wrong, but to also show that we can forgive. Griff was called for traveling, so 
he had to be penalized, but that doesn't mean he had to be cut off the team. 
</P>
<P>
So, how do you comment on what Griff said? What do you say when someone asks if 
you're racist or anti-Semitic? 
</P>
<P>
"NBC Nightly News" asked me that the other night and they wanted to see me 
sweat, but I don't feel any guilt. I'm not racist. I'm not anti-Semitic. I 
think it is a waste of time being anti-anything. 
</P>
<P>
But I also won't let this (controversy) keep me, as a black nationalist, from 
talking about problems of the black people and asking questions about how these 
problems came about. What is happening now is that people are looking at the 
Griff comments and reading racism or anti-Semitic thoughts in everything we do, 
like the "Terrordome" single. 
</P>
<P>
I'm not a racist, but I am inquisitive and I hope that when I keep asking 
questions, people don't respond to them by saying it's a racist question 
because there is no such thing as a racist question. There are only racist 
answers. 
</P>
<P>
What does it mean to you to be a black nationalist? 
</P>
<P>
Black nationalist means that since we are viewed upon as a separate 
constituency that is judged by our characteristics instead of our character, it 
means we have to network among each other. 
</P>
<P>
If we were able to say, "Hey, I'm black and I'm American, but an American 
first," white people are not going to see us that way. They see us first as 
black and then deal with us from there. In view of that, we have to network 
with other black people for our own protection and self interest. 
</P>
<P>
Is your dream an equal society? 
</P>
<P>
That'll happen once whites have a better understanding of blacks. Now you have 
a problem of white people running away, like we are aliens or something. 
</P>
<P>
Are you calling for separatism? 
</P>
<P>
I'm looking for separate development so that we can get to the level of the 
rest of society. We've got to create our own businesses and future so that we 
don't always have to be in the position of going to the white man for a job. 
</P>
<P>
What was the message of "Terrordome'? 
</P>
<P>
It was my perspective on what happened in 1989 in black America and also what 
happened to Public Enemy. 
</P>
<P>
The most controversial line in the song is the reference to crucifixion. Didn't 
you realize that you would rekindle the whole anti-Semitic controversy and also 
get accused of taking yourself too seriously by comparing what you went through 
to Christ? 
</P>
<P>
I'm an artist and that's my imagery. You can't let your artistry be intimidated 
by the fear that people are going to misinterpret you. To me, there's a bit of 
paranoia going on here. I was talking about a media crucifixion. 
</P>
<P>
In light of the attack on the record, would you have taken the crucifixion 
lines out of the record if you were making it again today? 
</P>
<P>
Hell no. There's nothing offensive in that record at all. But the media keeps 
asking me about the Jewish community, hoping I'll say something that gives them 
another good story. But how can I blame the Jewish community? There are certain 
factions in the community that are looking out for the best interests of the 
whole community. They are doing what they are supposed to do. 
</P>
<P>
If black people were to get hostile at implications and assumptions, hell man, 
white people would be on the edge every second. 
</P>
<P>
What's the new album's message? Is it going to make white people edgy? 
</P>
<P>
The thing I'm asking is, "Why do whites run from blacks?" I call it the Jackass 
Theory: Just acting Caucasian kills a simple solution. As long as white people 
believe they are white and pure, they will treat us as something different. My 
great-grandfather is white, but I'm black and what difference does it make? But 
in white eyes it means my great-grandfather and his kids were contaminated so 
they was basically knocked out of the game. 
</P>
<P>
The day that white people stop acting white and start acting more human, in the 
sense that we are all in this (expletive) together, we will come to some point 
where everybody will get a piece of the pie. 
</P>
<P>
Did you get any pressure from CBS Records about the lines in "Terrordome?" 
</P>
<P>
They try to give me pressure, but I say, "You don't like me, you cut me off and 
I'm out of here tomorrow. My next album will go bootleg gold." But they don't 
want to cut off a million-plus sales. 
</P>
<P>
CBS understands what I'm doing. If I went to the company and said, "White 
people need to die tomorrow, Jews are (messing in our affairs)" . . . if I had 
a twisted mentality like that, I would expect CBS to react differently. 
</P>
<P>
I know they are under pressure from some groups, but the only thing they can 
point to about the anti-Semitism issue is the Griff interview and their 
interpretation of four lines in a song. I have explained those lines, but still 
some people refuse to accept it. 
</P>
<P>
Do you get strength from the black community? 
</P>
<P>
I'm very proud of what I get from the black community because I think once I 
told people, "Don't believe the hype no matter how much news the white media 
throws at 'em," the kids know not to believe that bull. The point of "Fear of a 
Black Planet" is like, hey, we are all in this together. My great-grandfather 
was white. It wasn't like his kids died. His kids were just considered black. 
The so-called white male wants to see the image of himself. If he doesn't see 
the image of himself, he thinks, "Oh man, my family tree is poisoned." 
</P>
<P>
The racist view of white people in the Western world is the same Aryan 
principle, where Aryan people used to check the bloodline. If you had any kind 
of Jewish infiltration in your blood, you weren't pure. Black people didn't 
have anything to do with that. But people seem to want to blame black people 
for some (things) that white people did in Germany and Europe. 
</P>
<P>
My No. 1 question in "Fear of a Black Planet": Is white America ready to deal 
with the rise of black male intellectualism and black male capitalism? Because 
once a brother gets into hustling, they are going to win. Once a brother gets 
into anything, because it's that extra drive we've got because we get beat down 
in so many areas. 
</P>
<P>
Did you think there was a time when you thought you might not be able to battle 
back? 
</P>
<P>
I understand it's all an intellectual game (dealing with the media and 
criticism). . . . The minute you wilt intellectually, you lose. You can't get 
intimidated. You've got to fight for what you believe in as long as you're 
right. 
</P>
</TEXT>
